WEBVTT

00:06.000 --> 00:12.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

01:08.539 --> 01:09.665
Amanda!

01:12.109 --> 01:13.406
Thanks, Benny!

01:14.978 --> 01:16.878
Thank you very much.
Have a good day.

01:19.149 --> 01:20.912
Hi, T.J. Hi, Molly.

01:20.951 --> 01:22.009
Hi, Amanda.

01:22.052 --> 01:23.519
Hi, Amanda.
How was your week?

01:23.554 --> 01:26.079
A little slow, but it'll pick up.

01:26.123 --> 01:27.215
So, what's good today?

01:27.257 --> 01:29.282
The blackberries are very nice.

01:30.270 --> 01:31.570
[Raspberries.]

01:31.695 --> 01:35.529
Actually, I could use a pound
of raspberries, please.

01:35.566 --> 01:36.931
[Thank you.]

01:41.104 --> 01:43.095
Good morning, Abe.
Charlie, Welcome back.

01:43.140 --> 01:46.732
Thanks. Hey, I'm sorry to hear
about you guys closing out.

01:47.811 --> 01:48.591
What?

01:48.631 --> 01:50.511
Do you have any idea
what you gonna do now?

01:51.248 --> 01:52.772
What did you smack me for?

01:52.816 --> 01:56.445
Business is a little slow but
we're not closing.

01:56.487 --> 01:58.717
He is confused.

01:58.755 --> 02:01.555
You know, I got some nice shiitakes
over here. You should look at them.

02:02.626 --> 02:03.803
Where did all the portobellos go?

02:03.827 --> 02:06.489
They're gone.
Valderon wanted them.

02:06.663 --> 02:08.631
Oh, good, you spotted him.

02:08.664 --> 02:10.257
Never even heard of him.

02:10.300 --> 02:12.495
Not Valderon, the other one.

02:12.536 --> 02:14.197
What...

02:14.238 --> 02:16.030
I don't remember seeing you
here before.

02:16.070 --> 02:17.238
Are you always here?

02:17.274 --> 02:21.408
Well, only when absolutely necessary.
It's a long trip.

02:21.445 --> 02:23.276
These are for you.

02:23.313 --> 02:24.940
Peekytoes. Marvelous.

02:24.982 --> 02:26.950
I wouldn't know
what to do with a crab.

02:26.984 --> 02:29.674
But thanks anyway. Bye.

02:36.627 --> 02:39.289
Weren't you just over there?

02:39.329 --> 02:43.197
It's always important to remember
that the wind from one door closing

02:43.233 --> 02:44.495
opens another.

02:44.535 --> 02:46.833
Pick my crabs, Amanda.

02:46.870 --> 02:49.532
Your mother wants you to
start living up to your potential.

02:49.573 --> 02:51.040
My mother is dead.

02:51.074 --> 02:52.701
Now, that's no reason
to ignore her.

02:53.777 --> 02:55.210
Open your nose!

02:55.245 --> 02:57.372
He was very unpleasant.

02:57.414 --> 02:59.348
Well, 59 dollars.

03:05.355 --> 03:07.755
Oh, don't let that one get away!

03:16.770 --> 03:17.970
Got you!

03:18.570 --> 03:19.870
Oh, no.

03:20.670 --> 03:21.870
Hi.

03:22.105 --> 03:26.098
I'm sorry, but something
is about to crawl up your pants.

03:29.947 --> 03:32.102
You may think
I'm some kind of freak

03:32.142 --> 03:35.242
but I was just
trying to help you.

03:35.986 --> 03:38.254
- Jesus!
- Sorry.

03:38.788 --> 03:41.555
- Frisky little guy.
- Not for long.

03:42.095 --> 03:43.825
He is gonna be lunch in my restaurant.

03:43.860 --> 03:45.122
Really?

03:45.162 --> 03:47.320
Yeah. I'm making something.

03:47.835 --> 03:49.700
Something very...

03:50.540 --> 03:51.933
Napoleonic.

03:52.073 --> 03:53.665
Crab Napoleon, actually.

03:54.675 --> 03:58.004
- Should be very special.
- Special.

03:59.646 --> 04:00.945
I'm sure it will be.

04:02.082 --> 04:04.194
You don't look like you're
in the restaurant business.

04:04.218 --> 04:07.119
- No? Why not?
- The suit.

04:07.154 --> 04:09.434
- Are you?
- No. Well, I...

04:09.474 --> 04:11.919
Yes, I'm starting
a restaurant that's about to open.

04:11.959 --> 04:15.520
And as a matter of fact
I just lost my chef.

04:15.562 --> 04:18.156
And it looks like
you've misplaced your crustacean.

04:18.197 --> 04:20.325
- It was a pleasure to meet you.
- Yeah, you too.

04:20.365 --> 04:22.028
Good luck.

04:22.069 --> 04:23.900
You too.

04:23.937 --> 04:26.201
Look Am, I found
your little wandering friend.

04:26.240 --> 04:28.265
Now, don't go
leaving these behind.

04:28.308 --> 04:30.840
Oh, goodness. Oh, god.

04:31.340 --> 04:33.037
Why did I buy these?

04:33.080 --> 04:35.514
I'm Gene O'Reilly.
It's been nice meeting you.

04:41.388 --> 04:42.782
Oh, your change!

04:56.837 --> 04:57.837
Hey.

04:58.839 --> 05:00.363
I made you some coffee.

05:00.407 --> 05:02.932
Thanks.
Ow, those are heavy.

05:02.976 --> 05:04.443
What are you doing with those?

05:04.478 --> 05:06.940
Don't ask.
I had the weirdest morning.

05:06.980 --> 05:07.940
Really?

05:07.980 --> 05:09.576
First I met this guy,
Gene O'Reilly.

05:09.616 --> 05:11.679
He said he was a friend of mom's.
Do you know him?

05:11.719 --> 05:13.779
Gene O'Reilly...

05:13.820 --> 05:16.282
No, I don't think so.
It doesn't ring a bell.

05:16.322 --> 05:18.114
I think he was a crazy person.

05:19.892 --> 05:22.656
And then Charlie asked me how I felt
about us closing.

05:24.063 --> 05:25.325
He's back, huh?

05:26.099 --> 05:27.830
So, did he asked you out?

05:28.140 --> 05:31.159
Tia Stella, stop changing
the subject.

05:34.106 --> 05:36.734
We agreed to run
this restaurant together.

05:38.511 --> 05:39.511
Okay.

05:41.247 --> 05:44.375
The new landlord's
raised the rent.

05:44.417 --> 05:47.580
We're not making it, sweetie,
we have it for some time.

05:47.620 --> 05:49.485
How much did he raised the rent?

05:49.522 --> 05:51.615
To 5000 dollars a month.

05:51.657 --> 05:54.182
- 5000? He can't do that.
- Well, he did.

05:55.094 --> 05:58.154
So, then we can go to a bank
and get a loan.

05:58.197 --> 06:01.492
I've already tried that and
the way things are going,

06:01.534 --> 06:03.968
the bank doesn't have the faith
that we can pay it back.

06:04.003 --> 06:07.268
But we've been here 70 years.

06:11.477 --> 06:13.775
- I'm sorry.
- No, I'm sorry, Amanda.

06:13.813 --> 06:15.446
No, it's my fault.

06:15.586 --> 06:17.272
Come on, what is
that they always say?

06:17.316 --> 06:19.944
That the wind from one door slamming
opens another?

06:19.985 --> 06:23.580
- What?
- Did I say it wrong?

06:23.622 --> 06:26.216
I'm not very good with proverbs,
you know.

06:26.992 --> 06:30.553
Come on, let's go get something to eat.
I'm starving.

06:38.838 --> 06:41.600
Ever since Henri Bendel
first opened in New York,

06:41.640 --> 06:44.870
Bendel's stood as New York's
most elegant store for women.

06:44.910 --> 06:47.635
Now, Henri's grandson, Jonathan
continues that tradition

06:47.675 --> 06:51.038
with the first four-star luxury
restaurant ever in a department store.

06:51.140 --> 06:52.970
After an exquisite meal
at Jonathan's,

06:53.010 --> 06:54.840
our guests will have
the run of the store.

06:54.880 --> 06:57.616
It's a whole new approach to
fine dining and shopping.

06:57.790 --> 06:59.682
You'll see next week.
Thank you all for coming.

06:59.722 --> 07:01.154
Excuse me, I've heard

07:01.194 --> 07:03.728
you spent 4 million dollars
on a 75 seat restaurant.

07:03.762 --> 07:04.956
That's a heavy gamble.

07:04.997 --> 07:07.659
Well madam, it's not a gamble
if you have the right ingredients.

07:07.700 --> 07:09.531
Again, thank you all.

07:10.202 --> 07:11.202
- Tom...
- Yes?

07:11.440 --> 07:13.100
There is a very thin girl

07:13.140 --> 07:15.250
- in your office making herself at home.
- Oh, Christ, that's Chris.

07:15.274 --> 07:17.369
Now, Lois, what is she doing
in my office without me?

07:17.409 --> 07:19.976
I don't know. But I
offered her a sandwich.

07:20.016 --> 07:21.880
With butter and jelly.

07:26.619 --> 07:27.619
Chris.

07:29.054 --> 07:32.353
I just downloaded my schedule
onto your computer.

07:32.391 --> 07:34.188
I hope you were using a condom.

07:34.226 --> 07:36.057
- What?
- Oh, nothing.

07:37.396 --> 07:39.887
I'll see you at lunch.

07:39.932 --> 07:41.832
- Lunch.
- Goodbye.

07:46.972 --> 07:51.003
Oh my god.
She did it in red.

07:51.043 --> 07:54.479
Sharing your cyberspace.
That's a big step for you, Tom.

07:54.513 --> 07:57.726
You know, I was actually gonna take her
to a nice lunch today and just break up with her.

07:57.750 --> 08:00.548
- We've had three dates.
- Getting too heavy for you?

08:00.586 --> 08:03.282
No, I just know
exactly where it's going.

08:03.322 --> 08:04.448
Look at this.

08:04.490 --> 08:06.856
This is happiness over time.

08:06.892 --> 08:08.154
You keep track of this?

08:08.193 --> 08:11.959
Yeah. You see after the third date
happiness drops precipitously.

08:11.997 --> 08:14.227
It's because first
everyone's very well mannered.

08:14.266 --> 08:16.632
No one really expects
anything to happen.

08:16.669 --> 08:20.029
By the fourth date it becomes a relationship
at which point it becomes a minefield

08:20.069 --> 08:23.029
of these secret meanings
and these unmet expectations and...

08:23.776 --> 08:28.007
Lois, look at this: we've had three dates,
she's downloading her schedule.

08:28.047 --> 08:30.229
Like, you know, they start questioning
"When is he gonna marry me?"

08:30.253 --> 08:31.430
"What are our kids
gonna look like?"

08:31.454 --> 08:33.861
And I am thinking, you know,
"Don't spend every weekend with her"

08:33.885 --> 08:36.197
and if I spend too much time at the office
is she gonna get suspicious?

08:36.221 --> 08:39.782
And it becomes a round
of these fights and making up,

08:39.825 --> 08:41.535
when at first it was just...

08:41.576 --> 08:42.587
fun.

08:42.626 --> 08:44.325
I believe you've overlooked something.

08:44.363 --> 08:48.197
The information you need, Tom,
is what you do after date three

08:48.233 --> 08:51.202
that makes every one
so miserable.

08:51.340 --> 08:52.669
What I do?

08:52.705 --> 08:55.196
No. Don't touch that.
Put that down. Put it down.

08:56.909 --> 08:59.309
Your airplane fetish
is starting to worry me.

08:59.345 --> 09:03.679
In 1961 Howard Hughes flew
a paper airplane

09:03.716 --> 09:05.577
from the Golden Nugget
to the Sands.

09:05.617 --> 09:06.840
It was 4.2 miles.

09:07.886 --> 09:10.548
One of these days
I'm gonna break that record.

09:10.589 --> 09:13.649
It's all in the adjustable
sweep-back of the wings.

09:13.692 --> 09:15.091
Look at that.

09:15.127 --> 09:18.688
Wasn't Howard Hughes the guy
who never got out of his pajamas?

09:19.832 --> 09:21.631
No, that's Hugh Hefner.

09:21.667 --> 09:23.567
John Starks is the man.

09:23.602 --> 09:24.967
He do 9 elbows last night.

09:25.004 --> 09:26.972
Okay, shut up. Come here.

09:27.006 --> 09:28.006
Taste this.

09:34.680 --> 09:38.116
- It's good.
- You do realize you can't lie?

09:38.150 --> 09:39.640
Oh, it stinks.

09:39.685 --> 09:42.051
It tastes like blue cheese and dirt.

09:42.087 --> 09:45.079
There is only one thing
that tastes worse than blue cheese and dirt.

09:45.124 --> 09:46.489
Rum raisins.

09:47.860 --> 09:51.956
Look... I'm really sorry we have to close.

09:53.265 --> 09:56.257
We can get jobs
in another restaurant.

09:56.301 --> 09:59.031
Sure, we can take our own ad
if we can afford it.

09:59.071 --> 10:03.633
"Situation wanted: Shitty chef and sous-chef
seek restaurant to ruin".

10:05.244 --> 10:08.442
Shitty chef and...

10:08.780 --> 10:09.780
We need a prayer.

10:09.815 --> 10:11.204
Here we go.

10:11.984 --> 10:13.561
Will you have any dessert today, Howard?

10:13.585 --> 10:15.815
Oh, I can't.
I got my cholesterol results.

10:15.854 --> 10:17.287
Oh, you don't wanna know.

10:17.322 --> 10:19.552
All I can say is,
no more desserts, Howie.

10:19.591 --> 10:20.717
I know.

10:20.759 --> 10:22.556
- Hi everybody.
- Hi.

10:22.594 --> 10:26.496
Big news. "La bodega",
on the corner, evicted.

10:26.532 --> 10:29.262
I've never liked that guy anyway.

10:29.301 --> 10:32.464
Well, at least we've still
got a place to eat lunch, huh?

10:33.272 --> 10:37.902
Uh... actually...
there's something I wanna tell you.

10:37.943 --> 10:38.943
I can't believe...!

10:38.977 --> 10:40.777
We'll never get a cab
at this time of the day.

10:41.781 --> 10:43.974
The cell phone!

10:44.116 --> 10:46.816
This is awful, I don't like it.
I don't understand it.

10:46.852 --> 10:49.612
That's terrible.
Where am I gonna eat my lunch?

10:50.989 --> 10:53.082
Bill, you don't like the food anyway.

10:53.125 --> 10:55.389
I love that cheesy chicken.

10:55.427 --> 10:58.089
Howard, be honest.

10:58.130 --> 10:59.825
You're not here for the food either.

10:59.865 --> 11:02.240
Don't give up, it's too soon.
You'll get better.

11:02.640 --> 11:04.735
We love you, Amanda.

11:05.938 --> 11:07.633
I love you, guys.

11:07.673 --> 11:11.734
You're a loyal, wonderful people and

11:11.777 --> 11:17.181
you deserve a 'Southern Cross'
like it used to be, when mom was here.

11:20.452 --> 11:24.411
I try but
I'm not my mom.

11:25.691 --> 11:26.691
I'm sorry.

11:51.984 --> 11:56.444
...for too many years.
Just do it! What?

11:56.488 --> 11:58.922
...until Thursday,
I need a phone call.

11:58.957 --> 12:00.549
Thank you very much.
No, not you.

12:00.592 --> 12:01.592
Excuse me!

12:02.209 --> 12:04.187
Where are we?
This isn't Chanterelles.

12:04.229 --> 12:05.473
Do I have to do everything for you?

12:05.497 --> 12:07.294
Excuse me! You're a cab!

12:09.835 --> 12:12.626
Oh, wait honey. You know what?
It's that way, honey.

12:15.407 --> 12:16.596
You!

12:17.876 --> 12:19.468
Oh, god.

12:19.511 --> 12:20.876
Not now.

12:22.981 --> 12:24.915
Perfect, a little person.

12:26.485 --> 12:27.747
Listen, do you know where...?

12:27.786 --> 12:29.276
- Hello.
- Hi.

12:29.321 --> 12:30.583
Do you two know each other?

12:31.590 --> 12:34.559
Her crab bit me this morning.

12:34.593 --> 12:35.593
Really?

12:36.428 --> 12:39.226
Do you know where
this restaurant is, Chanterelles?

12:39.264 --> 12:42.594
- Sure, it's two blocks that way.
- No, no.

12:43.001 --> 12:45.069
We're here.
We might as well just eat.

12:45.109 --> 12:47.733
Besides, I feel like a little crab.

12:47.773 --> 12:50.173
A little bad crab. It's so unfair.

12:51.810 --> 12:55.473
Well, lunch is sort of over.
Forever.

12:56.582 --> 12:58.946
- So you're just teasing me?
- What?

12:59.084 --> 13:00.612
This morning in the market...

13:00.652 --> 13:03.246
With the Crab Napoleon and the souffle...

13:03.288 --> 13:04.722
It sounded amazing.

13:04.723 --> 13:05.723
Thank you.

13:06.691 --> 13:10.286
Do you have a menu
that we could look at?

13:11.162 --> 13:12.162
Of course.

13:18.236 --> 13:20.363
That's one more humiliation.

13:28.980 --> 13:30.311
Right this way.

13:39.324 --> 13:41.884
Two new customers.

13:41.926 --> 13:43.757
Maybe it's a sign.

13:45.296 --> 13:46.820
Oh my god.

13:46.865 --> 13:48.662
- He's here.
- Who?

13:48.700 --> 13:50.167
The guy from the market.

13:50.201 --> 13:53.793
I told him that I can make Crab Napoleon
with pommes... something

13:53.838 --> 13:56.139
and he's showed up.

13:56.174 --> 13:58.233
Well, just tell him
we're out of here.

13:58.276 --> 14:00.608
No, tell him we've closed.

14:00.645 --> 14:02.513
- I can't do that.
- Now, I tell him.

14:02.582 --> 14:05.247
No! Then he's gonna leave.

14:05.283 --> 14:07.012
Now, that's the idea,
isn't it?

14:07.051 --> 14:09.679
No! I want him to stay.

14:09.721 --> 14:14.540
Then we're just gonna have to make the
Crab Neopolitan... Napalm...

14:14.580 --> 14:16.552
- Napoleon.
- Whatever.

14:17.061 --> 14:18.061
How?

14:21.399 --> 14:23.799
You better go find
one of your mom's recipes.

14:24.236 --> 14:27.927
Okay, I'll just...
I'll go upstairs now.

14:34.846 --> 14:36.438
Crab Napoleon.

14:37.482 --> 14:40.178
This is gonna suck.

14:40.218 --> 14:42.618
Well, if she's ever
gonna find her inspiration,

14:42.654 --> 14:44.645
please, let it happen now.

14:54.199 --> 14:56.740
Hey. So, did you found a recipe?

14:56.780 --> 14:58.063
Oh, no.

14:58.937 --> 15:01.098
But I found these
in my mom's box.

15:01.139 --> 15:03.369
Wow. Those are nice.

15:03.408 --> 15:05.706
Hey, maybe we can sell them
and pay the rent.

15:05.743 --> 15:07.711
Nolan, they are my mom's.

15:08.646 --> 15:12.477
- No. So, crabs... Boiled?
- Yeah.

15:15.186 --> 15:17.177
So, how did you hear about us?

15:17.222 --> 15:18.587
Sorry that took so long.

15:18.623 --> 15:20.784
It'll just be here
in a couple of minutes.

15:20.825 --> 15:22.349
Will you both be having the crab?

15:22.393 --> 15:24.054
- Please.
- No.

15:24.095 --> 15:29.533
Listen, I was wondering if you could just do
a very simple Chicken Paillard.

15:31.803 --> 15:34.181
One Chicken Paillard
for the mistake he's with.

15:34.221 --> 15:36.000
Girls like that
really get to me.

15:36.041 --> 15:38.735
- But she's perfect for him.
- No, she's not.

15:38.775 --> 15:40.110
Check the hair.

15:40.144 --> 15:42.635
Every strain in place,
just like his.

15:43.748 --> 15:45.682
I can fix my hair.

15:45.717 --> 15:48.049
Not like that. You can't, Amanda.

15:48.086 --> 15:50.680
So, she has perfect hair.
Big deal.

15:50.722 --> 15:52.166
No, it's not just the hair,
it's the skin.

15:52.190 --> 15:55.284
She's got that kind of skin.
It's silky, like butter.

15:55.326 --> 15:57.487
It's called makeup and,
Nolan, you're not helping.

15:57.528 --> 16:00.497
You've got to be born with that kind of skin.
And check out the sharp suit.

16:00.531 --> 16:02.328
She trippin' far,
she cut her leg off.

16:02.367 --> 16:05.768
- And look at the shoes!
- Nolan, shut up! Okay?

16:05.803 --> 16:08.271
You're wrong.
He's not happy with her.

16:08.306 --> 16:09.636
He couldn't be happy

16:09.676 --> 16:12.607
with somebody with perfect skin
and perfect hair

16:12.643 --> 16:15.976
and perfect wardrobe with
goddamned matching shoes.

16:16.016 --> 16:19.276
And if you can't see that,
then I feel sorry for you.

16:19.317 --> 16:21.717
Inevitably she'll self-destruct.

16:22.720 --> 16:27.987
I'm just under a little stress today,
that's all. But I can handle it.

16:28.026 --> 16:29.755
If you say so.

16:31.029 --> 16:33.429
Okay. Now.

16:34.299 --> 16:38.736
We are going to make
the most delicious Crab Napoleon.

16:38.770 --> 16:40.795
Where is the recipe?

16:40.838 --> 16:42.897
I told you I couldn't find one.

16:42.941 --> 16:44.465
But we'll improvize.

16:44.509 --> 16:47.376
Just bring me...
everything we have.

16:47.412 --> 16:49.107
Everything we have.

16:49.147 --> 16:51.012
And the crabs, are they cooked?

16:51.049 --> 16:54.450
The crabs... are dead.

16:55.453 --> 16:57.284
There's nobody here, honey.

16:57.322 --> 16:59.688
Well, it's late for lunch.

16:59.724 --> 17:02.625
So... "Cleveland".

17:09.166 --> 17:10.862
Can I interest you in a martini?

17:12.136 --> 17:13.364
Not for me.

17:13.404 --> 17:14.803
No, thank you.

17:19.810 --> 17:23.804
You know, just once
I'd like to make something really great.

17:24.949 --> 17:32.949
Just have everything come together so perfectly
that just one bite is ecstasy.

17:36.060 --> 17:39.291
Did you ever noticed
how many words there are for "delicious"?

17:40.999 --> 17:42.364
Savory,

17:43.368 --> 17:44.630
tasty,

17:45.670 --> 17:47.763
scrumptious,

17:47.805 --> 17:49.295
delightful,

17:50.108 --> 17:51.336
succulent,

17:52.577 --> 17:54.238
mouth-watering...

17:56.839 --> 17:59.339
Huh... Nolan?

18:00.218 --> 18:01.218
Wow! Freaky!

18:01.252 --> 18:03.846
People that we don't know
want their food.

18:05.556 --> 18:07.353
Where did that come from?

18:07.392 --> 18:09.451
